        {
            "id": "b708c47927eb4fa18640c",
            "questionText": "A police radar gun emits a frequency of $!$8.0\\,\\text{GHz}$!$. A car is moving towards the police officer, and the radar gun detects a reflected frequency of $!$8.00015\\,\\text{GHz}$!$. Assuming the speed of radio waves is the speed of light, which is approximately $!$3.0 \\times 10^8\\,\\text{m/s}$!$, calculate the speed of the car in $!$km/h$!$.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "6860a7023b0e494eb18f9",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by converting the given frequencies into standard units and computing the frequency shift $!$\\Delta f$!$. Calculate the difference between the reflected frequency and the emitted frequency.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "150000"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "Hz",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "5fd087bf-30b8-4f0e-9ea8-08c67db5840f",
                        "f09a3cf7-42e1-4878-b989-bb756bfc1f03"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "fcde8af395334db2b6a43",
                    "stepText": "Great, now that you have the frequency difference, identify the Doppler effect relation that links $!$\\Delta f$!$, the emitted frequency $!$f_0$!$, the speed of the car $!$v$!$, and the speed of light $!$c$!$ for a reflected wave from a moving object. Which formula correctly represents this relation?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "a20069a8-ca33-4e26-93ce-87c105e52c27",
                        "bbf4917b-1be4-4827-b1ae-ddfdaa7124a9",
                        "8004f091-3866-4725-923f-566d362ee31a"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta f = \\frac{2 f_0 v}{c}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta f = \\frac{f_0 v}{c}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta f = \\frac{2 v}{c}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "002d4ee2ea744de4a1da9",
                    "stepText": "Now that you have selected the appropriate Doppler effect relation, use it to solve for the car\u2019s speed $!$v$!$ in meters per second by substituting $!$\\Delta f = 1.5 \\times 10^5 Hz$!$, $!$f_0 = 8.0 \\times 10^9 Hz$!$, and $!$c = 3.0 \\times 10^8 m/s$!$ into the formula, then isolate and calculate $!$v$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "2812.5"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m/s",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "a20069a8-ca33-4e26-93ce-87c105e52c27",
                        "bbf4917b-1be4-4827-b1ae-ddfdaa7124a9",
                        "8004f091-3866-4725-923f-566d362ee31a"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "df49f403fe584d35ac861",
                    "stepText": "Excellent work! Finally, convert the car's speed from meters per second to kilometers per hour. Recall that to convert $!$m/s$!$ to $!$km/h$!$, you multiply by 3.6. Compute the final speed in $!$km/h$!$.",
