        {
            "id": "e06ec878727a40c5a6e81",
            "questionText": "An astronomer observes a distant galaxy emitting light with a known wavelength of $!$650 nm$!$, while the observed wavelength on Earth is $!$682 nm$!$. Given that the speed of light is approximately $!$3.0 \\times 10^8\\ m/s$!$, determine the galaxy's velocity relative to Earth in $!$km/s$!$ (indicating its direction of motion from the sign of the velocity).",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "e01a099024024989b0509",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the redshift formula. Which of the following expressions correctly represents the redshift $!$z$!$ in terms of the emitted wavelength $!$\\lambda$!$ and the observed wavelength $!$\\lambda'$!$?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "21d1d259-b66f-4509-8897-4feba2f2b3e6",
                        "ba45dfc9-7996-4dda-bd14-1d7f21675597"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$z = \\frac{\\lambda' - \\lambda}{\\lambda}\\,$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$z = \\frac{\\lambda - \\lambda'}{\\lambda'}\\,$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$z = \\frac{\\lambda' + \\lambda}{\\lambda}\\,$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "5477599c2ce74c85b2a18",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now, using the correct formula from the previous step, calculate the redshift $!$z$!$ from the given wavelengths where $!$\\lambda = 650\\,nm$!$ and $!$\\lambda' = 682\\,nm$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "0.04923"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "21d1d259-b66f-4509-8897-4feba2f2b3e6",
                        "ba45dfc9-7996-4dda-bd14-1d7f21675597"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "808c0db83bc947f7a760b",
                    "stepText": "Let's move forward by identifying the formula that relates the redshift $!$z$!$ to the velocity $!$v$!$ for light in the non-relativistic limit. Which of the options below provides the appropriate relation?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "21d1d259-b66f-4509-8897-4feba2f2b3e6"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v = z\\, c\\,$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v = \\frac{c}{z}\\,$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v = \\frac{z}{c}\\,$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "f1238f400cbc4c9ebbd6e",
                    "stepText": "Now, use the chosen formula to calculate the galaxy's velocity in meters per second using the redshift you computed and the speed of light $!$c = 3.0 \\times 10^8\\,m/s$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
